english:
  title: The Pavilion of Sunflowers
  author: Cho Wei
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the summer following my exile to Yongwan, I found my lodgings cramped and stifling in the oppressive heat. So I chose a high and open spot in the garden and built a small pavilion of a few bays, roofed with thatch, where five or six could sit comfortably. Yet around me stood crowded houses with scarcely a gap between them, and the garden itself was but a few paces across, containing only some dozens of sunflowers—green stems and tender leaves stirring gently in the summer breeze. Thus I named it the Pavilion of Sunflowers.

    One day a visitor asked me: "The sunflower is surely the most delicate and humble of plants. In ancient times, men honored grasses and flowers for their noble character or fragrant virtue, naming their dwellings after the pine, bamboo, plum, chrysanthemum, orchid, and other plants of distinction. I have never heard of anyone naming their residence after something so humble and weak. What merit do you find in the sunflower? Is there some deeper meaning here?"

    I replied: "The inequality of things reflects the nature of creation itself. Value and worth take ten thousand different forms. The sunflower is indeed the most delicate and common of all plants—if we compare it to people, it is like the coarse and unremarkable of the lowest station. The pine, bamboo, plum, chrysanthemum, orchid—these are plants of strength and noble character, fragrant with virtue. In people, they represent those of outstanding excellence, rare and apart, whose names and virtue shine brightly. I now find myself banished to these remote and lonely shores, despised and cast aside by all. Would it not bring shame upon myself and ridicule from others to name my dwelling after the pine and bamboo, the plum and orchid? To match my exile with base things, seeking no farther than what lies near—this is my intention.

    Moreover, I have heard it said that heaven produces no useless thing, no wasted talent. Even the lowliest plants—the wild herbs and common greens—the ancients would not disdain. And the sunflower possesses two virtues! It turns ever toward the sun, bending with the light—can this not be called loyalty? It shelters the earth below—can this not be called wisdom? Loyalty and wisdom are the very foundation of the virtuous servant: loyalty means serving one's lord with undivided sincerity; wisdom means discerning all things without confusion between right and wrong. These are virtues the noble struggle to attain, and what I have long admired. How then can something possessing such beauty be lumped together with common, trivial plants and despised?

    From this perspective, it is clear that not only the pine and bamboo, the plum and orchid, deserve to be called precious. Though I now live in exile, every moment of sleep and every meal comes from the grace of my lord. In the leisure after my afternoon rest and simple meal, I recite the poems of Shen Xiuwen and Sima Guang, and my heart turns naturally toward the light. Can it be wrong then to name my pavilion after the sunflower?"

    The visitor laughed and said: "I understood only the first part of your meaning, but not the second. Now that I have heard the significance of your pavilion, it is truly beyond reproach." And with that, he departed with a smile.

    Written in the sixth month, first ten days, of the year Gimmi.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Shen Xiuwen (沈休文, 441-513) and Sima Guang (司馬君實, 1019-1086) were both celebrated poets and statesmen known for their moral integrity and wisdom—virtues the author wishes to emulate through his sunflower metaphor.
  - key: ''
    value: The date 'year Gimmi' (己未) refers to 1619 in the Korean calendar system.
